WEBVTT

00:01.506 --> 00:04.789
You are listening to a message from First Baptist Church, Wichita Falls.

00:05.290 --> 00:14.319
For more information about First Baptist, click the link in the show notes or go to FBCWN.org.

00:14.339 --> 00:17.502
Today's message comes from senior pastor, Dr. Bob McCartney.

00:18.443 --> 00:22.947
Let's open our Bibles this morning to Matthew chapter 1 verse 23.

00:23.888 --> 00:25.850
Matthew chapter 1 verse 23.

00:26.190 --> 00:30.194
I'm beginning a short series of messages leading up to Christmas Eve.

00:30.402 --> 00:32.104
entitled, Remember.

00:32.164 --> 00:37.210
And what we want to remember is the true meaning of Christmas.

00:37.851 --> 00:45.180
You know, it's very interesting to me that at Christmastime we have a unique opportunity with the gospel.

00:45.961 --> 00:53.270
And that is that the world which for 11 months of the year is almost entirely secular.

00:53.350 --> 00:56.434
I mean, they want nothing to do with the supernatural.

00:56.546 --> 01:03.017
They seem to move just a little bit in our direction, and they really want to embrace the supernatural.

01:03.758 --> 01:13.835
You see it in the entertainment at Christmastime, miracle on 34th Street, that there could be a miracle, that something miraculous could happen.

01:14.517 --> 01:22.450
I mean, Bing Crosby and Danny Kay saved the Generals ski resort in Vermont in White Christmas,

01:22.562 --> 01:26.869
An angel appears to George Bailey and it's a wonderful life.

01:26.929 --> 01:35.003
The secular world moves just a little bit toward this desire to embrace the supernatural and the miraculous.

01:35.744 --> 01:36.806
There's a reason for that.

01:37.627 --> 01:41.714
The Bible says that God has set eternity in man's heart.

01:42.338 --> 01:47.964
that there is something about us that longs for something infinite, something eternal.

01:48.004 --> 01:50.426
There is something in us that craves that.

01:50.707 --> 01:53.049
Now in our flesh we rebel against it.

01:53.930 --> 01:58.395
But for some reason at Christmastime we move a little bit toward that.

01:59.095 --> 02:05.642
And so as Christians let's embrace that and let's move toward the supernatural ourselves.

02:05.682 --> 02:09.586
Let's embrace what the Bible says about the supernatural because

02:09.826 --> 02:13.150
The Christmas story is almost entirely supernatural.

02:14.071 --> 02:19.417
You have an angel that appears to marry and then to Joseph.

02:19.437 --> 02:25.004
You have an angels, angels, a host of angels that appear to the shepherds.

02:25.765 --> 02:37.138
A mysterious moving star appears in the sky and guides Middle Eastern wise men all the way to Bethlehem to meet this newborn king.

02:37.762 --> 02:41.166
a couple well beyond the age of childbearing.

02:41.767 --> 02:45.953
Zacharias and Elizabeth conceive and give birth to a child as well.

02:46.313 --> 02:47.435
And his name is John.

02:48.216 --> 02:55.585
He will be the forerunner of the Messiah proclaiming that the way of the Lord is coming and that people should be prepared for it.

02:56.686 --> 03:05.618
But the greatest miracle of Christmas is the one that makes all other miracles really pale in comparison.

03:06.370 --> 03:10.736
And that is the miracle that we call the incarnation.

03:11.437 --> 03:17.205
Incarnation is not necessarily a word that you would perhaps normally use in your vocabulary.

03:17.265 --> 03:23.614
So when we speak of the incarnation of Christ, what do we mean by that?

03:24.555 --> 03:34.930
Well, the incarnation is the doctrine that God the Son without ceasing to be God took on human flesh

03:35.170 --> 03:37.794
and became fully human.

03:37.814 --> 03:40.258
Fully human, fully God.

03:41.159 --> 03:46.286
It is the miracle that God stepped into His creation.

03:47.128 --> 03:53.938
Now when I used a word in that definition, some of you immediately pushed back just a little bit when I called it the doctrine.

03:54.879 --> 04:03.252
Well doctrine doesn't necessarily mean some dusty old teaching that belongs in a seminary classroom and has no practicality.

04:04.213 --> 04:04.914
Actually,

04:05.378 --> 04:08.762
The incarnation is imminently practical.

04:09.342 --> 04:14.989
And when you come to understand the incarnation, it will help you face temptation.

04:15.069 --> 04:21.716
You will come to understand how to face temptation because Jesus Christ came in the flesh.

04:21.736 --> 04:28.984
The incarnation will help you understand prayer and embrace the reality of prayer.

04:29.585 --> 04:34.130
It will help you deal with loneliness, with fear and yes, even grief.

04:34.690 --> 04:53.672
The fact that Jesus Christ came, that God the Son clothed Himself in human flesh and became fully human and fully divine is one of the most practical truths in all of the Bible, but is also one of the most powerful truths in the Bible.

04:54.513 --> 04:54.954
J.I.

04:55.054 --> 05:02.002
Packer, one of my favorite theologians of the last century, wrote, the supreme mystery of the gospel.

05:02.818 --> 05:06.343
is the mystery of the incarnation.

05:07.385 --> 05:13.354
And while I cannot fully explain it because the Bible teaches it, I fully embrace it.

05:14.235 --> 05:32.082
That this mysterious truth that Jesus was both fully God and fully man is something that we as Christians need to once again wrap our arms around and embrace this Christmas season because it is the meaning of Christmas.

05:32.866 --> 05:44.437
The real meaning of Christmas is that Jesus Christ, God the Son, came to fully embrace all it means to be human.

05:45.278 --> 05:51.685
Now Matthew's gospel records the Christmas story from Joseph's point of view.

05:52.606 --> 06:01.074
Luke chapter one gives us a lot of Mary's point of view, but Matthew gives us Joseph's point of view.

06:01.602 --> 06:11.696
And he tells us the story of how Joseph was very troubled that Mary came to him and honestly told him that she was with child and an angel told her that the Holy Spirit had conceived this child within her.

06:12.537 --> 06:15.060
And Joseph was deeply troubled at all this.

06:15.181 --> 06:19.186
I mean, embracing the supernatural for Joseph in that moment was not easy.

06:20.248 --> 06:30.802
But one night Joseph went to sleep and in a dream an angel appeared to him and told him, Joseph, don't be afraid to take Mary to be your wife because everything she told you is true.

06:31.586 --> 06:39.018
And you're going to give this little boy a name, and his name is going to be Jesus, because he's going to save his people from their sins.

06:40.279 --> 06:49.293
And then the Bible tells us in Matthew records that all of this took place to fulfill a prophecy.

06:50.135 --> 06:53.400
And that prophecy was uttered by the prophet Isaiah.

06:53.840 --> 06:57.426
It is recorded in Isaiah chapter 7 verse 14.

06:57.666 --> 07:02.151
It is recorded again here in Matthew chapter 1 verse 23.

07:03.213 --> 07:20.834
Behold, the virgin will conceive and give birth to a son, and they shall name him Immanuel, which translated means God with us.

07:22.496 --> 07:27.122
Now when people read that, they are sometimes a bit confused, and that is,

07:27.522 --> 07:35.571
that when the Hebrew refers to Emmanuel as a name, it is more of what we would call a title.

07:36.692 --> 07:40.617
Jesus wasn't referred to as Emmanuel in common conversation.

07:41.358 --> 07:43.580
It wasn't a nickname that was given to him.

07:44.041 --> 07:47.905
It was more of a title that was bestowed upon him.

07:48.986 --> 07:54.032
And Emmanuel simply means God in our very presence.

07:54.873 --> 07:55.954
So what does it mean?

07:56.834 --> 08:00.300
for Jesus to be God incarnate.

08:01.041 --> 08:06.331
God in human flesh, it simply means that the incarnation has taken place.

08:07.272 --> 08:09.035
And here's what the incarnation means to us.

08:09.096 --> 08:15.026
First of all, the incarnation means that God came to us.

08:15.938 --> 08:27.851
that God came to us, that He is not a distant deity, that He is not somewhere remotely off into the heavens, and He spun the world in motion, and He kind of took His hands off of the whole thing.

08:28.612 --> 08:32.096
That is not the way the incarnation works.

08:33.757 --> 08:43.208
See, last weekend Stephen preached a wonderful message that I did listen to last Sunday morning, along with you, from John chapter 1.

08:43.888 --> 08:45.330
And to refresh your memory,

08:45.538 --> 08:55.712
In John chapter 1, John begins not at the conception of Christ and Mary.

08:55.732 --> 08:57.435
He doesn't begin with Matthew's story.

08:57.955 --> 08:59.598
John begins at the beginning.

09:00.359 --> 09:03.143
And I don't mean like the beginning of Genesis 1-1.

09:03.503 --> 09:05.786
He begins at the beginning before the beginning.

09:05.826 --> 09:07.489
The beginning before Genesis 1-1.

09:08.029 --> 09:10.793
He says, in the beginning was the Word.

09:11.735 --> 09:14.258
And the Word was with God.

09:14.562 --> 09:16.884
and the word was God.

09:17.945 --> 09:23.371
So one of the things that we need to understand is who is this word, this logos?

09:24.151 --> 09:32.340
In the Greeks, to the Greeks, the logos was the logical principle that explained and ordered the universe.

09:32.360 --> 09:34.462
That is what logos is.

09:34.482 --> 09:40.247
For the Hebrews word, the word of God, was his self-revelation.

09:40.327 --> 09:42.930
It was his self-expression.

09:43.330 --> 09:48.655
and his complete revelation of his character and his power and his authority.

09:49.336 --> 10:04.551
And so when John uses that expression that the Word was with God and the Word was God, he's telling us something about the Trinitarian nature of God, that God is Father, that God is Son, that God is Holy Spirit.

10:05.532 --> 10:11.698
And then in verse 14 of that passage, the Bible explodes with meaning.

10:12.066 --> 10:33.913
when the Bible tells us that the Word became flesh, the Logos of God, the ordering principle of the universe, the self-expression of God, the Word of God, the Word became flesh, that He took on humanity.

10:34.613 --> 10:38.418
Now when John uses the word flesh, he doesn't use it like Paul uses it.

10:38.562 --> 10:42.266
Paul uses it to indicate our sinful nature.

10:43.147 --> 10:49.334
But John is using it to express our natural physical being.

10:50.255 --> 11:06.674
And so when John says the word took on flesh, then the supernatural ordering principle of the universe, the self-revelation of God himself, clothes himself in humanity in a human body.

11:07.842 --> 11:11.087
The Word became flesh and He dwelt among us.

11:11.127 --> 11:13.310
He pitched His tent right here.

11:13.350 --> 11:16.134
That's what that Word dwelt meant.

11:17.416 --> 11:25.709
And He pitched His tent among us and we beheld His glory, glory as the only begotten of the Father full of grace and truth.

11:26.770 --> 11:30.676
That expression only begotten is one that needs to be understood.

11:30.716 --> 11:37.426
We're going to talk about the incarnation and what it means for God to clothe Himself in human flesh

11:38.178 --> 11:49.372
That expression has sometimes been confused, and quite honestly, it has been perverted by some denominations and religious groups into heresy.

11:50.453 --> 12:04.370
When John says the only begotten of the Father, only begotten is an expression that we need to explore, because the word there is monogenesis.

12:04.930 --> 12:08.355
And mono-genesis means mono one.

12:08.815 --> 12:15.084
Genesis, we get our word generation, one of a kind, one of a kind, unique.

12:16.526 --> 12:21.073
It does not, begotten does not mean created.

12:22.294 --> 12:33.330
Now there are some groups that teach that Jesus is a created being, somehow subordinate to God the Father and the Holy Spirit.

12:34.242 --> 12:37.367
That is not New Testament Christianity.

12:38.189 --> 12:45.602
New Testament Christians believe in the co-equality of father, son, and Holy Spirit.

12:46.744 --> 12:48.647
That's what New Testament Christians believe.

12:48.787 --> 12:51.412
And if you don't believe that, you're not a New Testament Christian.

12:53.035 --> 12:53.415
You're not.

12:55.258 --> 12:56.380
By the way, you sing that.

12:56.460 --> 12:58.885
Even the secular world sings that every year.

12:58.945 --> 12:59.666
You sing it.

13:01.282 --> 13:22.350
You sing it when you hear the words to hark the herald angels sing, veiled in flesh the Godhead see, hail the incarnate deity, pleased with men as men to dwell, Jesus our Emmanuel.

13:23.151 --> 13:24.072
You sing it every year.

13:24.112 --> 13:25.594
The secular world sings it.

13:26.315 --> 13:31.282
I'm in Starbucks and Mariah carries belting that out over the speakers in there.

13:32.162 --> 13:47.924
It's an amazing thing that we get so close, the secular world gets so close to embracing the real truth of Christmas and yet keeps it at a distance.

13:48.444 --> 13:53.511
But practically for us, it means that you matter to God.

13:54.172 --> 13:55.634
You matter so much.

13:55.810 --> 13:57.332
that He didn't send a messenger.

13:57.552 --> 13:58.954
He didn't send an angel.

13:59.195 --> 14:01.017
He didn't shout His love from heaven.

14:01.438 --> 14:05.504
He sent His Son to show His love on earth.

14:06.806 --> 14:10.511
You are not abandoned by some distant deity.

14:10.591 --> 14:17.901
He came to be among us, to be one of us, and to endure everything this world could dish out.

14:18.923 --> 14:20.325
That's how much God loves you.

14:21.867 --> 14:23.890
Everything changed when the King showed up.

14:26.146 --> 14:32.175
back in 2020 when the COVID pandemic was, uh, was, you know, in full swing.

14:32.956 --> 14:40.247
There were certain that by the way, I got sick with COVID and please don't tell me it wasn't real because I, I mean, I wasn't imagining what I had.

14:40.267 --> 14:40.748
Okay.

14:42.691 --> 14:49.661
But there were some hospitals that were overwhelmed, especially in the Northeast and in some colder areas.

14:50.142 --> 14:53.106
And those hospitals were just, just overwhelmed with, with people.

14:54.178 --> 14:59.727
And there was one particular nurse who was interviewed by a television reporter about something that happened.

14:59.767 --> 15:08.161
And she said, everything changed in our hospital when one day the CEO showed up in the emergency room where all these people were.

15:08.863 --> 15:19.420
And he put on PPE, put on the protective gear and he took a mop and he started mopping and disinfecting the areas where we had had patients.

15:20.241 --> 15:20.562
See,

15:21.442 --> 15:22.924
That's what incarnation is.

15:23.004 --> 15:25.486
It comes to get involved in our mess.

15:26.768 --> 15:32.073
It comes to risk, and he comes to be a part of everything that we're struggling with.

15:32.534 --> 15:36.057
He's not sitting off in some office somewhere telling us what to do.

15:36.438 --> 15:38.360
He's coming and showing us what to do.

15:39.381 --> 15:42.104
The incarnation means that God came to us.

15:42.144 --> 15:46.848
Secondly, the incarnation means that God identifies with us.

15:46.868 --> 15:48.370
There are more passages than

15:48.866 --> 15:57.177
than Matthew 1, 23, and even John chapter 1 that gives us an understanding of the incarnation.

15:57.197 --> 15:59.680
And one of those is in the book of Hebrews.

16:00.721 --> 16:16.562
The writer of the book of Hebrews, though we do not know exactly who it was, tells us in Hebrews chapter 2 verse 17, therefore he had to be made like his brethren in all things.

16:17.058 --> 16:27.852
so that he might become a merciful and faithful high priest in all things pertaining to God to make propitiation for the sins of the people.

16:28.593 --> 16:37.744
For since he himself was tempted in that which he has suffered, he is able to come to the aid of those who are tempted.

16:39.146 --> 16:45.234
Theologians for generations have looked into those verses and made a

16:45.410 --> 16:52.739
particular point of those first few words, he had to be made like his brethren.

16:53.480 --> 16:56.343
There is a moral imperative in that.

16:56.423 --> 16:58.746
It's a statement of necessity.

16:59.046 --> 17:09.519
The incarnation that Christ would come to enter his creation, that the infinite would become finite, that the eternal would step into time.

17:10.040 --> 17:12.102
It was a moral necessity.

17:12.423 --> 17:15.186
There was no other way.

17:16.034 --> 17:21.520
for Jesus to become our great high priest.

17:22.241 --> 17:31.892
And the book of Hebrews explains to us without Jesus becoming our great high priest to offer the sacrifice, which was himself, to satisfy the wrath of God.

17:32.192 --> 17:34.815
Then there's no way of salvation.

17:35.656 --> 17:44.786
The incarnation was an absolute necessity for your salvation, for my salvation, for the salvation of the world.

17:45.858 --> 17:48.382
that He had to be made like us.

17:48.402 --> 17:51.667
He had to enter into His creation.

17:52.588 --> 17:55.072
It is complete identification.

17:56.394 --> 17:59.980
It was not a simulation.

18:00.000 --> 18:01.642
It wasn't pretend.

18:02.604 --> 18:09.654
Jesus wasn't just some divine tourist who showed up and viewed the world and then left.

18:10.516 --> 18:12.218
No, He actually got involved.

18:12.258 --> 18:14.642
It was complete assimilation.

18:14.786 --> 18:16.107
into our world.

18:17.008 --> 18:28.180
And the writer of Hebrews says that he had to do that to make propitiation for the sins of the people, propitiation.

18:28.200 --> 18:36.449
If you're reading from some translations, it might say to be the atoning sacrifice for the sins of the world.

18:37.430 --> 18:41.074
That is what it means, but the word propitiation is a

18:41.314 --> 18:44.477
a bit of a deeper and richer word.

18:44.497 --> 18:47.080
And sometimes big words are good words.

18:48.661 --> 18:49.822
And in this case, it's true.

18:51.184 --> 18:59.852
You see, propitiation means the sacrifice that completely satisfies.

19:01.694 --> 19:10.162
It is the sacrifice that is the full, sufficient, completely adequate sacrifice.

19:10.722 --> 19:11.783
to satisfy.

19:11.803 --> 19:12.805
What does it satisfy?

19:13.726 --> 19:15.588
Well, it satisfies your sin debt.

19:16.769 --> 19:18.692
We have a debt that we cannot pay.

19:18.792 --> 19:21.635
We cannot do anything to repay our sin debt to God.

19:22.937 --> 19:29.745
By propitiation, Jesus became the sacrifice that satisfied, that paid in full our sin debt.

19:32.368 --> 19:37.394
But it also is the sacrifice that satisfies the wrath of God.

19:38.754 --> 19:41.117
whom did Jesus save us from?

19:41.358 --> 19:41.958
I'll tell you who.

19:43.080 --> 19:45.003
We want to say hell sometimes, and that's true.

19:46.204 --> 19:49.469
But what Jesus saved us from is the wrath of God.

19:49.849 --> 19:52.493
God came to save us from God.

19:54.415 --> 20:02.026
Because God is a God of love, but He is also a God of wrath and punishment for those who reject Him and refuse to repent and turn from sin.

20:04.049 --> 20:07.954
See, the Bible tells us in Hebrews chapter 4, verse 15,

20:08.386 --> 20:17.635
We do not have a high priest who cannot sympathize with our weaknesses, but one who has been tempted in all things as we are yet without sin.

20:19.617 --> 20:29.387
One of the necessities of the incarnation was not only that he would become a faithful and merciful high priest, and he would make propitiation for our sins, but it is also very practical.

20:30.308 --> 20:36.914
And it's practical for you this afternoon and tomorrow morning and on Tuesday night, it is the practicality

20:37.410 --> 20:41.895
of him assisting us when we are tempted to sin against God.

20:42.977 --> 20:48.643
He can sympathize with our weaknesses because he has been tempted in all points as we are.

20:49.764 --> 20:53.489
He was fully tempted because he was human.

20:53.929 --> 20:56.993
He did not sin because he was God.

20:59.976 --> 21:02.640
Jesus' temptations were not shadow boxing.

21:03.641 --> 21:04.722
They were very real.

21:05.538 --> 21:07.401
They were full temptations.

21:07.441 --> 21:10.565
He felt the full force of every temptation.

21:11.727 --> 21:18.677
And yet because of his divine nature, he did not sin because God cannot sin.

21:19.478 --> 21:32.978
Now that is a mystery that I don't fully understand, but what I do know is this, that he came to get in the mess of this world with us to show us that he loves us, he cares for us,

21:33.602 --> 21:37.306
and that we can rely on him when we ourselves are tempted."

21:39.307 --> 21:47.455
You see, since he himself was tempted in that which he has suffered, he is able to come to the aid of those who are tempted.

21:48.296 --> 21:55.943
2013, something happened in the Middle East and it's a rare occurrence, maybe once every 40 or 50 years.

21:56.904 --> 22:03.090
But a cold front blew down from the north and dumped a bunch of snow on the Middle East.

22:03.810 --> 22:09.038
And if you think Texas drivers are bad in snow, you ought to see the Middle East when it snows.

22:09.879 --> 22:12.584
I mean, they're just totally unaccustomed to snow.

22:12.604 --> 22:14.226
I have no idea what to do with it.

22:15.188 --> 22:17.812
A Mon Jordan was particularly hard hit.

22:17.872 --> 22:22.018
Over six inches of snow fell in a Mon Jordan of all places on Earth.

22:23.200 --> 22:26.365
And people were out in their cars and they're spinning around.

22:26.405 --> 22:27.427
They're getting stuck.

22:27.447 --> 22:28.789
They can't move.

22:28.829 --> 22:32.274
And one particular fellow, he got stuck in a snow drift.

22:32.386 --> 22:43.698
He's trying to get his car out when the car behind him, the driver jumps out, another fellow jumps out and they begin to rock his car and they push him out and when they kind of freed him for that, he stopped.

22:43.718 --> 22:52.187
He jumped out to thank them and he was absolutely stunned when he was face to face with King Abdullah II of Jordan.

22:53.048 --> 22:54.750
He was the driver of the car behind him.

22:56.332 --> 22:58.514
See, the king could have said, hey, go help.

22:59.042 --> 23:01.224
to his security detail, hey, go out that guy.

23:01.244 --> 23:02.645
I'm going to sit here in my comfortable car.

23:03.907 --> 23:08.531
But the king got out and he showed up.

23:08.551 --> 23:10.573
See, when the king shows up, everything changes.

23:12.215 --> 23:13.496
And that's what happens to us.

23:13.636 --> 23:21.103
The king of the universe showed up and he endured all that we endure, yet without sin.

23:21.183 --> 23:25.367
And he is able to sympathize with us in our weaknesses.

23:25.688 --> 23:28.050
That means that your failure shouldn't

23:28.674 --> 23:31.657
It shouldn't cause you to fear his rejection.

23:32.058 --> 23:35.562
It should cause you to run to him because of his sympathy.

23:36.803 --> 23:44.052
God does not roll his eyes at your struggle because God knows the battle you are facing in temptation.

23:45.773 --> 23:49.578
And he loves you so much that he cares for you.

23:50.158 --> 23:56.786
Finally, the incarnation means that God cares for you deeply.

23:58.146 --> 24:05.054
The incarnation means as God came in human flesh that he cares for you so deeply.

24:06.455 --> 24:13.803
In John chapter 1 verse 10, John writes, he was in the world and the world was made through him.

24:13.823 --> 24:14.644
He's the Creator.

24:14.945 --> 24:21.071
The Creator shows up as part of the creation and the world did not know him.

24:22.133 --> 24:25.456
Verse 11 is one that always gets my attention.

24:25.476 --> 24:27.058
He came to his own

24:27.714 --> 24:32.120
And those who were his own did not receive him.

24:33.662 --> 24:37.306
In other words, his own did not welcome him.

24:38.768 --> 24:40.411
They didn't welcome him at all.

24:40.431 --> 24:48.621
I don't know if you've ever had the experience of being somewhere where you really weren't welcome.

24:49.122 --> 24:55.410
Now maybe it wasn't overt hostility, but maybe you got an invitation by mistake.

24:56.386 --> 24:59.191
few years ago, my wife and I are convinced this happened to us.

25:00.453 --> 25:10.930
That we got an invitation to come to a function and we thought it a bit unusual, but we thought, well, since we got invited, we ought to show up.

25:10.950 --> 25:22.610
So we knocked on the door and the door opened and the hostess did seem a little somewhat confused that we were there, but we were there and we went in.

25:23.618 --> 25:27.382
And after a few awkward minutes, I looked at Mary Ann and she looked at me.

25:27.502 --> 25:30.406
I said, I don't think we're supposed to be here.

25:32.028 --> 25:35.231
There was just an awkwardness about the whole occasion.

25:36.513 --> 25:39.396
And so I did what any self-respecting person would do.

25:41.098 --> 25:41.579
I left.

25:44.562 --> 25:47.966
I looked over at Mary Ann and said, you know what, I don't think we're welcome here.

25:48.106 --> 25:51.570
I mean, they weren't just mean to us or anything, but it was just weird.

25:52.290 --> 25:55.894
And I looked at Mary and she looked at me and she said, you know, I didn't really want to come anyway.

25:55.954 --> 25:57.136
So why don't we just leave?

25:59.499 --> 26:02.182
If you're not welcome, you usually just leave.

26:02.903 --> 26:09.551
Well, Jesus wasn't welcome, but he stayed, but he stayed.

26:11.433 --> 26:13.055
We didn't receive him with open arms.

26:13.095 --> 26:15.137
He said, Oh, thank, thank the father.

26:15.177 --> 26:17.060
He finally sent his son to save us.

26:18.061 --> 26:18.962
People didn't say that.

26:20.386 --> 26:24.770
He was rejected and abused and betrayed and ultimately crucified.

26:26.832 --> 26:27.493
Why did he stay?

26:27.513 --> 26:29.935
I won't tell you why he stayed.

26:32.358 --> 26:49.554
He stayed because God so loved the world that he gave his only begotten one of a kind son that whosoever believes in him.

26:49.762 --> 26:58.753
whosoever believes in Him will not perish but have eternal life."

27:00.015 --> 27:00.636
That's why he stayed.

27:02.598 --> 27:18.418
He stayed so that you could be rescued from your sin and your selfishness so that you could receive eternal life.

27:20.226 --> 27:22.249
and be rescued from the wrath of God.

27:23.832 --> 27:24.593
That's why I stayed.

27:26.235 --> 27:34.048
So this morning, if you've never received Christ, I played with you.

27:35.049 --> 27:38.655
The greatest gift of Christmas is the gift of Jesus.

27:41.339 --> 27:44.804
It's His gift, and it's Him as a gift.

27:46.768 --> 27:48.370
And He wants to come into your life

27:49.250 --> 27:55.540
and he wants to save you and rescue you from your sin.

27:55.560 --> 28:04.934
And this morning, you could pray a prayer right where you're sitting, to call on his name, and he will hear an answer.

28:06.156 --> 28:11.744
The Bible says that all who call on the name of the Lord will be saved.

28:13.247 --> 28:18.194
Anyone who asks Jesus

28:19.906 --> 28:26.837
sincerely and in faith will receive the gift of eternal life.

28:28.500 --> 28:47.090
Now, if you just say the words, no, but if in faith believing that God came in human flesh and as a man, he died on a cross for your sins to pay your price.

28:48.962 --> 28:55.771
And if in sincerity of faith, you believe that he was raised from the dead and he is alive today.

28:55.811 --> 29:01.298
And you ask him to come into your life to save you, to be your Lord and Master.

29:01.599 --> 29:02.560
He will come.

29:03.301 --> 29:04.122
That is a promise.

29:06.445 --> 29:10.270
You've been listening to a message from First Baptist Church, which is not false.

29:10.290 --> 29:18.962
For more information about First Baptist, including gathering times and locations, click the link in the show notes or go to FBCWF.org.

29:19.234 --> 29:20.562
We'll see you next week.

